\section{Summary} \label{sec:conc}
In this work, we investigate dynamic yaw control of wind farms for optimal power extraction. To this aim, we extended the optimal control framework OSP-Wind used in previous studies for dynamic axial induction control to include yaw. The potential of dynamic yaw control is evidenced based on a $4\times4$ wind-farm demonstration case, both for laminar and turbulent background flow conditions. It is shown that wind-farm efficiency can be increased significantly for all considered control cases, and that dynamic yaw control is more effective than dynamic underinduction control for the given wind farm. The turbulent flow cases indicate that dynamic yaw control outperforms simple wake redirection through static yaw control. Further, the fact that the optimizer harnesses non-trivial flow features, e.g. the curling of wakes originating from yawed turbines, justifies the application of high-fidelity models in deriving control strategies, even for relatively simple laminar flows. 

Suggestions for future work include the application of the proposed methodology to larger wind farms or different wind-farm layouts, for which possible interaction between turbine columns could potentially reduce the benefits of yaw-based wake redirection control. Further, incorporating a structural dynamics solver into the framework is required to asses whether the derived control strategies contribute to additional fatigue loading, and would allow to perform a multi-objective optimization in which structural loading and power extraction are balanced. 

